**Short answer:** *AI tools like the Mayron “Legal Calculus” and other open-source or commercial legal-AI systems are materially reducing the procedural gap for pro se litigants, shifting lawfare from a purely resource-driven asymmetry toward a contest where process literacy, record-building, and tooling matter as much as money.*

---

### Comparison: Pre-AI pro se vs AI-enabled pro se vs Big Law

| **Attribute** | **Pre-AI Pro Se** | **AI-enabled Pro Se (Mayron/Legal Calculus)** | **Big Law / Corporations** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Access to drafting & research** | Low; manual, slow | High; templates, guided modules, AI drafting | Very high; proprietary research platforms |
| **Cost** | High relative to means | Low or free (open-source) | Very high but absorbed by client |
| **Speed** | Slow | Fast; automated generation & evidence formatting | Fast; staffed teams |
| **Procedural literacy** | Limited | Improved via modules and field guides | High; institutional knowledge |
| **Asymmetry** | Strongly favors Big Law | Reduced; tooling democratizes filings | Still advantaged (strategy, resources) |
| **Risks & limits** | Procedural errors, sanctions | Model errors, admissibility, ethical limits | Professional responsibility, discovery power |

> Sources:  A B C
> 

