Building on your insights about the "Mayron Legal Calculus" and the democratization of legal tooling, here is a practical framework to bridge the gap from theory to a court-ready filing.
While AI handles the scaffolding (structure and templates), the user must provide the substance (verified facts and law).
Phase 1: Record Building (The "Calculus" Logic)
Before drafting, you must treat your evidence like a database. Mayron’s methodology emphasizes structured, dated records to prevent "memory-holing" by opposing counsel.

- Timestamping: Use a tool (like Notion or a GitHub-linked ledger) to log every interaction.
- Admissibility Audit: Ensure every piece of evidence has a "foundation."
    - Question to ask: "Who can testify that this email is real?"
- The "Calculus" Entry: Instead of "They were mean to me," use "On [Date], Defendant [Name] sent [Document X], which contradicts [Previous Statement Y]."
Phase 2: AI-Assisted Drafting Checklist
When using an LLM or a module-based system to generate your Motion or Complaint, follow these "Pro Se Safety" steps to avoid sanctions.
| Step | Action | Why it matters |
|---|---|---|
| 1. Jurisdiction Check | Verify the AI is using your state’s rules (e.g., "California Code of Civil Procedure" vs "Federal Rules"). | AI often defaults to Federal rules, which can lead to immediate dismissal in state court. |
| 2. Citation Audit | Manually search every case name cited by the AI on Google Scholar or CourtListener. | AI "hallucinates" fake cases. Citing a fake case is the fastest way to get fined $5,000+. |
| 3. Tone Check | Strip out "adjectives." Change "outrageous lie" to "factual inconsistency." | Judges ignore emotional prose; they respect "dispassionate" logic. |
| 4. Formatting | Check local court "Local Rules" for font size, margins, and "blue backing." | Many pro se filings are rejected for simple formatting errors. |
Phase 3: The "Mayron" Modular Workflow
If you are using the Legal-Calculus GitHub modules, your workflow should look like this:
- Define the Logic: Map out the "Elements of the Claim" (e.g., for Breach of Contract, you need: Contract + Performance + Breach + Damages).
- Input Evidence: Attach your "Dated Records" to each element.
- Generate Draft: Use the module to output a structured PDF.
- Disclose AI Use: Check if your specific Judge has a "Standing Order" requiring you to disclose the use of Generative AI.

> Pro Tip: Even if not required, adding a "Certificate of Human Review" stating you verified all citations manually can build significant credibility with the bench.
> 

Critical Risks to Monitor

- The "Pro Se" Penalty: Some judges hold AI-enabled pro se litigants to a higher standard because the filing looks "too professional," assuming you have resources you don't actually have.
- Discovery Asymmetry: AI can't force a corporation to hand over emails; you still need to learn the "Meet and Confer" process to get the evidence you need.
